Interview:
Linux is an open-source, highly customizable operating system mainly used in servers and development, while Windows is a user-friendly, commercial operating system widely used on desktops with strong software support.

Difference between Unix and Linux

Interview:
Unix is a proprietary operating system developed by vendors, while Linux is an open-source, Unix-like system that is free, flexible, and widely used in modern computing.

Unix → An original, proprietary operating system developed in the 1970s
Linux → An open-source, Unix-like operating system built later and inspired by Unix

Feature	                  Unix	                        Linux
Origin	                  Developed by AT&T Bell Labs	  Created by Linus Torvalds
Source Code	              Mostly closed-source	        Open-source
Cost	                    Paid (licensed)	              Free (mostly)
Development	              Vendor-specific	              Community + companies
Flexibility	              Less customizable	            Highly customizable
Usage	                    Enterprise/legacy systems	    Servers, cloud, DevOps

